    <text>
        <body><div type="bibliography">
                
                <p><bibl> <ptr target="#smith-porcher1864"/>, n. <citedRange>16</citedRange></bibl>, whence
                    <bibl><ptr target="#SGDI"/> <citedRange>4850</citedRange></bibl> and                    
                    <bibl><ptr target="#OGIS"/> <citedRange>22</citedRange></bibl>;
                    <bibl><ptr target="#IGCyr"/> <citedRange>062900</citedRange></bibl>.
                    Cf. <bibl><ptr target="#Sammelbuch"/> <citedRange>10077</citedRange></bibl>;
                    <bibl><ptr target="#fraser1956"/>, p. <citedRange>50, footnote 2</citedRange></bibl>, whence 
                    <bibl><ptr target="#SEG"/> <citedRange>18.729</citedRange></bibl>; 
                    <bibl><ptr target="#chamoux1956"/>, p. <citedRange>31</citedRange></bibl>;
                    <bibl><ptr target="#SECir"/>, p. <citedRange>374</citedRange>, fig. 170 (only a photograph)</bibl>;
                    <bibl><ptr target="#bagnall1976"/>, p. <citedRange>26</citedRange></bibl>;                    
                    <bibl><ptr target="#laronde1987"/>, p. <citedRange>409, footnote 1</citedRange></bibl>.</p>
            </div><div type="edition" xml:lang="grc" xml:space="preserve">
                
                <ab>
                    <lb n="1"/><w lemma="βασιλεύς"><supplied reason="lost">Βασιλῆ</supplied></w> <persName type="ruler" key="Ptolemy II"><name nymRef="#Πτολεμαῖος"><supplied reason="lost">Πτ</supplied><supplied reason="undefined" evidence="previouseditor">ο</supplied><unclear>λε</unclear><supplied reason="lost">μ</supplied>αῖον</name></persName> <persName type="ruler" key="Ptolemy I and Berenice I"><rs type="epithet" key="Soteres"><w lemma="σωτήρ">Σωτήρων</w></rs></persName>
                    <lb n="2"/><persName type="attested" key="http://clas-lgpn2.classics.ox.ac.uk/cgi-bin/lgpn_search.cgi?id=V1-63217"><name nymRef="#Ἀρίστων"><supplied reason="lost">Ἀρ</supplied>ίστων</name> <persName type="attested" key="http://clas-lgpn2.classics.ox.ac.uk/cgi-bin/lgpn_search.cgi?id=V1-64913"><name type="patronymic" nymRef="#Λυσιφάνης">Λυσιφάνευς</name></persName></persName>
                    <lb n="3"/><w lemma="ἀνατίθημι">ἀνέθηκε</w>.
	 </ab>
            </div><div type="apparatus" xml:space="preserve">
            
                <p><app loc="1"><lem><supplied reason="lost">Βασιλῆ</supplied></lem>
                <rdg resp="#smith-porcher1864"><supplied reason="lost">Βασιλέα</supplied></rdg>
                </app>
                </p>
 </div><div type="translation" xml:lang="fr" xml:space="preserve">
            <p><supplied reason="subaudible">La statue du</supplied> <supplied reason="lost">roi</supplied> Ptolémée fils des Sôtères a été consacrée par Aristôn fils de Lysiphanès.</p>
         </div><div type="translation" xml:lang="en" xml:space="preserve">
            <p> <supplied reason="subaudible">The statue of</supplied> <supplied reason="lost">king</supplied> Ptolemy son of the Soteres was dedicated by Ariston son of Lysiphanes.</p>
         </div><div type="translation" xml:lang="it" xml:space="preserve">
            <p><supplied reason="subaudible">La statua del</supplied> <supplied reason="lost">re</supplied> Tolemeo figlio dei Soteri è stata dedicata da Ariston figlio di Lysiphanes.</p>
         </div><div type="translation" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="ar">
                <p>(تمثال) [الملك] بطليموس بن السوتيريس (المُنْقِذِين) كُرِسَ من قبل أريستون بن ليسيفانيس.</p>
            </div>
            <div type="commentary">
                
                <p>Smith and Porcher saw the stone «built into the corner of a wall in the restored part of the temple of Apollo, on the second story. As the inscribed face was turned inwards, 
                    this marble must have been taken from some earlier edifice». Because of its position, they could transcribe only part of it.</p>
                <p>The date is induced from the lack of titles for the parents and absence of Arsinoe, married in 279/8 (<bibl><ptr target="#fraser1956"/>, p. <citedRange>50, footnote 2</citedRange></bibl>); moreover, it might show that the quarrel
                    between Magas and Philadelphus did not become effective in the very first years of Philadelphus' reign (<bibl><ptr target="#bagnall1976"/>, p. <citedRange>26</citedRange></bibl>; <bibl><ptr target="#laronde1987"/>, p. <citedRange>409, footnote 1</citedRange></bibl>).</p>
	<p/>
            </div></body>
